\begin_layout Subsection
Quantum Probability Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A classical model decides the occurrence or non-occurence of all events
 simultaneously which is inconsistent with quantum mechanics.
 Indeed, in the quantum world, there are (non-commuting) events which cannot
 happen simultaneously.
 To accommodate this situation, we completely abandon the sample space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and define and reason directly about events.
 Thus a quantum probability space will consist of just two components: a
 set of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\qevents$
\end_inset

 and a probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\qevents\rightarrow[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 These components are defined as follows
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Maassen2010,Swart2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first assume an ambient Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hilb$
\end_inset

 and define the set of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\qevents$
\end_inset

 as 
\emph on
projections
\emph default
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hilb$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly to the classical case, a probability measure is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:\qevents\rightarrow[0,1]$
\end_inset

 satisfying: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\mathbbm{1})=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\qevents$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(A^{*}A)\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

