\begin_layout Standard
Concrete example: consider the two qubit Hilbert space with computational
 bases 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{1}$
\end_inset

.
 First, consider the two states 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ket{+}=\frac{\ket{0}+\ket{1}}{\sqrt{2}},\ket{-}=\frac{\ket{0}-\ket{1}}{\sqrt{2}}
\]

\end_inset

and consider the following families of projections: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Family I: 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{1}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Family II: 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{+}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{-}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In family I, all operators can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \lambda_{1}\proj{0}+\lambda_{2}\proj{1}~\middle|~\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2}\in\mathbb{C}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 In order to identify projectors among them, we need to solve the following
 two equations.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lambda_{1}\proj{0}+\lambda_{2}\proj{1} & = & \left(\lambda_{1}\proj{0}+\lambda_{2}\proj{1}\right)^{*}=\lambda_{1}^{*}\proj{0}+\lambda_{2}^{*}\proj{1}\\
\lambda_{1}\proj{0}+\lambda_{2}\proj{1} & = & \left(\lambda_{1}\proj{0}+\lambda_{2}\proj{1}\right)^{2}=\lambda_{1}^{2}\proj{0}+\lambda_{2}^{2}\proj{1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Therefore, we actually have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

, and there are only four projections: 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\proj{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbbm{1}=\proj{0}+\proj{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ket{+}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ket{-}}$
\end_inset

 of each projections are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c@{\qquad\qquad}c}
\begin{array}{rcl}
\phi_{\ket{+}}(0) & = & 0\\
\phi_{\ket{+}}(\proj{0}) & = & 1/2\\
\phi_{\ket{+}}(\proj{1}) & = & 1/2\\
\phi_{\ket{+}}(\mathbbm{1}) & = & 1
\end{array} & \begin{array}{rcl}
\phi_{\ket{-}}(0) & = & 0\\
\phi_{\ket{-}}(\proj{0}) & = & 1/2\\
\phi_{\ket{-}}(\proj{1}) & = & 1/2\\
\phi_{\ket{-}}(\mathbbm{1}) & = & 1
\end{array}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ket{+}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ket{-}}$
\end_inset

 gives two probability for family II as well.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c@{\qquad\qquad}c}
\begin{array}{rcl}
\phi_{\ket{+}}(0) & = & 0\\
\phi_{\ket{+}}(\proj{+}) & = & 1\\
\phi_{\ket{+}}(\proj{-}) & = & 0\\
\phi_{\ket{+}}(\mathbbm{1}) & = & 1
\end{array} & \begin{array}{rcl}
\phi_{\ket{-}}(0) & = & 0\\
\phi_{\ket{-}}(\proj{+}) & = & 0\\
\phi_{\ket{-}}(\proj{-}) & = & 1\\
\phi_{\ket{-}}(\mathbbm{1}) & = & 1
\end{array}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

